"\n## Problems\nLet $x$, $y$ and $z$ all exceed $1$ and let $w$ be a positive number such that $\\log_x w = 24$, $\\log_y w = 40$ and $\\log_{xyz} w = 12$. Find $\\log_z w$. Show that it is 060.\n\n## Informal proof\nThe [[logarithm]]ic notation doesn't tell us much, so we'll first convert everything to the equivalent exponential forms.\n\n$x^{24}=w$, $y^{40}=w$, and $(xyz)^{12}=w$. If we now convert everything to a power of $120$, it will be easy to isolate $z$ and $w$.\n\n$x^{120}=w^5$, $y^{120}=w^3$, and $(xyz)^{120}=w^{10}$.\n\nWith some substitution, we get $w^5w^3z^{120}=w^{10}$ and $\\log_zw=060$.\n\n## Formal statement\n```isabelle\ntheorem aime_1983_p1:\n  fixes x y z w :: nat\n  assumes ht : \"1 < x \\<and> 1 < y \\<and> 1 < z\"\n    and hw : \"0 \\<le> w\"\n    and h0 : \"ln w / ln x = 24\"\n    and h1 : \"ln w / ln y = 40\"\n    and h2 : \"ln w / ln (x * y * z) = 12\"\n  shows \"ln w / ln z = 60\"\n```\n\n## Structured informal proof\nStep 1: Convert the logarithmic equations to exponential form.\nStep 2: Raise each equation to the power of 120 to make the exponents of $w$ on the right-hand side multiples of 5.\nStep 3: Substitute the expressions for $x^{120}$ and $y^{120}$ into the equation for $(xyz)^{120}$.\nStep 4: Simplify the resulting equation to isolate $z^{120}$ and $w$.\nStep 5: Convert the resulting equation back to logarithmic form to find $\\log_z w$.\n\n## Lemmas\n### Lemma 1\nA lemma converting logarithmic equations to exponential form would be useful for step 1.\n\n### Code 1\n```isabelle\nlemma log_to_exp:\n  fixes a b :: real\n  assumes \"a > 0\" \"b > 0\" \"a \\<noteq> 1\"\n  shows \"log a b = c \\<longleftrightarrow> a^c = b\"\n```\n\n### Lemma 2\nA lemma raising both sides of an equation to the same power would be useful for step 2.\n\n### Code 2\n```isabelle\nlemma power_both_sides:\n  fixes a b c d :: real\n  assumes \"a = b\" \"c > 0\"\n  shows \"a^c = b^c\"\n```\n\n### Lemma 3\nA lemma converting exponential equations to logarithmic form would be useful for step 5.\n\n### Code 3\n```isabelle\nlemma exp_to_log:\n  fixes a b :: real\n  assumes \"a > 0\" \"b > 0\" \"a \\<noteq> 1\"\n  shows \"a^c = b \\<longleftrightarrow> log a b = c\"\n```\n\n### Lemma 4\nA lemma for the property of logarithms $\\log_{xyz} w = \\log_x w \\cdot \\log_y w \\cdot \\log_z w$ would be useful for simplifying the equations.\n\n### Code 4\n```isabelle\nlemma log_product_base:\n  fixes x y z w :: real\n  assumes \"x > 1\" \"y > 1\" \"z > 1\" \"w > 0\"\n  shows \"ln w / ln (x * y * z) = (ln w / ln x) * (ln w / ln y) * (ln w / ln z)\"\n```\n\n### Lemma 5\nA lemma for the property of logarithms $\\log_z w^{10} = 10 \\cdot \\log_z w$ would be useful for simplifying the equations.\n\n### Code 5\n```isabelle\nlemma log_power:\n  fixes z w n :: real\n  assumes \"z > 1\" \"w > 0\" \"n > 0\"\n  shows \"ln (w^n) / ln z = n * (ln w / ln z)\"\n```\n\nBy using these lemmas, the structured informal proof can be followed to prove the given theorem in Isabelle. The lemmas provide the necessary mathematical properties and conversions to facilitate the step-by-step proof."